# 📚 Reader Engine Modes Documentation

## 1. Standard Mode

### Overview  
Standard Mode presents text in **small grouped chunks (typically 3–5 words)**, centered on screen. It is optimized for **controlled, distraction-free reading**.

### Behavior  
- Text is split into fixed-size word groups  
- Words appear sequentially at a controlled pace (WPM-based)  
- No continuous motion (static transitions)  
- User maintains visual focus on a single point  

### Characteristics  
- Stable visual anchor  
- Predictable pacing  
- Minimal cognitive load  
- No scrolling required  

### Use Cases  
- Careful reading / comprehension  
- Studying or learning material  
- Users new to speed reading  
- Dense or technical text  

### Pros  
- High comprehension  
- Low eye strain  
- Easy to follow  

### Cons  
- Slower than Flow mode  
- Can feel mechanical  
- Fixed chunk size may not adapt to sentence structure  

---

## 2. Flow Mode

### Overview  
Flow Mode displays text as a **continuous horizontal stream**, similar to a teleprompter or marquee. It is optimized for **speed and natural reading rhythm**.

### Behavior  
- Text moves continuously across the screen  
- Speed controlled via WPM or animation timing  
- No chunking — full sentence flow  
- User tracks motion visually  

### Characteristics  
- Dynamic movement  
- Natural reading simulation  
- High-speed capability  
- Immersive experience  

### Use Cases  
- Skimming long content  
- Passive reading (e.g., narration-style)  
- Familiar or simple text  
- Speed reading practice  

### Pros  
- Faster reading speed  
- Feels natural and fluid  
- Better for long-form content  

### Cons  
- Lower comprehension for complex text  
- Can cause eye fatigue  
- Harder for beginners  

---

## 3. Adaptive Mode (Smart Mode)

### Overview  
Adaptive Mode is a **hybrid intelligent system** that dynamically switches between Standard and Flow modes based on **context, text length, and user behavior**.

### Behavior  
- Automatically selects reading mode:
  - Short text → Standard  
  - Long text → Flow  
- Monitors user interaction:
  - Active user → Flow mode  
  - Idle user → Standard mode  
- Can dynamically adjust reading speed (WPM)  

### Decision Logic (Current Implementation)

#### Text-Based Switching
- `< 120 words` → Standard Mode  
- `≥ 120 words` → Flow Mode  

#### Interaction-Based Switching
- User interaction (click/scroll) → Flow Mode  
- No interaction (> 3 seconds) → Standard Mode  

### Characteristics  
- Context-aware  
- Behavior-driven  
- Seamless transitions  
- No manual switching required  

### Use Cases  
- Default mode for most users  
- Mixed reading sessions  
- Productivity-focused environments  
- “Set and forget” experience  

### Pros  
- Best overall UX  
- Adapts to user behavior  
- Reduces manual control friction  
- Feels intelligent and modern  

### Cons  
- Less predictable behavior  
- Requires tuning (thresholds, timing)  
- Slightly more complex logic  

---

## 4. Mode Comparison Summary

| Feature                | Standard Mode | Flow Mode | Adaptive Mode |
|----------------------|-------------|----------|--------------|
| Text Display         | Chunked     | Continuous | Dynamic |
| Speed                | Medium      | High     | Variable |
| Comprehension        | High        | Medium   | Optimized |
| User Control         | Manual      | Manual   | Automatic |
| Motion               | Static      | Moving   | Mixed |
| Best For             | Study       | Speed    | General Use |

---

## 5. Recommended Default

- **Default Mode:** Adaptive  
- **Reason:** Provides the best balance between speed, comprehension, and usability  

